'''Castell Coch''' ({{IPA-cy|ˈkastɛɬ koːχ}}; {{Language with name/for||Welsh|Red Castle}}) is a 19th-century [[Gothic Revival]] castle built above the village of [[Tongwynlais]] in [[South Wales]]. The first castle on the site was built by the Normans after 1081, to protect the newly conquered town of [[Cardiff]] and control the route along the [[River Taff|Taff Gorge]]. Abandoned shortly afterwards, the castle's earth [[motte]] was reused by [[Gilbert de Clare, 7th Earl of Gloucester|Gilbert de Clare]] as the basis for a new stone fortification, which he built between 1267 and 1277 to control his freshly annexed Welsh lands. This castle was likely destroyed in the [[native Welsh]] rebellion of 1314. In 1760, the castle ruins were acquired by [[John Stuart, 3rd Earl of Bute]], as part of a marriage settlement that brought the family vast estates in South Wales.

[[John Crichton-Stuart, 3rd Marquess of Bute|John Crichton-Stuart]], the 3rd Marquess of Bute, inherited the castle in 1848. One of Britain's wealthiest men, with interests in [[architecture]] and [[antiquarian]] studies, he employed the architect [[William Burges]] to reconstruct the castle, "as a country residence for occasional occupation in the summer", using the medieval remains as a basis for the design. Burges rebuilt the outside of the castle between 1875 and 1879, before turning to the interior; he died in 1881 and the work was finished by Burges's remaining team in 1891. Bute reintroduced commercial [[viticulture]] into Britain, planting a vineyard just below the castle, and wine production continued until the [[First World War]]. The Marquess made little use of his new retreat and in 1950 his grandson, the [[John Crichton-Stuart, 5th Marquess of Bute|5th Marquess of Bute]], placed it into the care of the state. It is now controlled by the Welsh heritage agency [[Cadw]].

Castell Coch's external features and the [[High Victorian Gothic|High Victorian]] interiors led the historian David McLees to describe it as "one of the greatest Victorian triumphs of architectural composition."{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=31}} The exterior, based on 19th-century studies by the antiquarian [[G. T. Clark|George Clark]], is relatively authentic in style, although its three stone towers were adapted by Burges to present a dramatic silhouette, closer in design to mainland European castles such as [[Château de Chillon|Chillon]] than native British fortifications. The interiors were elaborately decorated, with specially designed furniture and fittings; the designs include extensive use of symbolism drawing on [[Classical mythology|classical]] and [[legend]]ary themes. [[J. Mordaunt Crook|Joseph Mordaunt Crook]] wrote that the castle represented "the learned dream world of a great patron and his favourite architect, recreating from a heap of rubble a fairy-tale castle which seems almost to have materialised from the margins of a medieval manuscript." {{sfn|Crook|2013|p=270}}

The surrounding [[Castell Coch Woodlands and Road Section|beech woods]] contain rare plant species and unusual geological features and are protected as a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]].

==History==

===11th–14th centuries===
[[File:Return from market - Castell Coch.jpg|thumb|[[Julius Caesar Ibbetson]]'s 1808 painting of the medieval ruins, based on his 1792 watercolour]]
The first castle on the Castell Coch site was probably built after 1081, during the [[Norman invasion of Wales]].{{sfn|Newman|1995|p=315}}{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=106}} It formed one of a string of eight fortifications intended to defend the newly conquered town of [[Cardiff]] and control the route along the [[River Taff|Taff Gorge]].{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=106}} It took the form of a raised, earth-work [[motte]], about {{convert|35|m}} across at the base and {{convert|25|m}} on the top, protected by the surrounding steep slopes.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|pp=105–106}} The 16th-century historian Rice Merrick claimed that the castle was built by the Welsh lord [[Ifor ap Meurig]], but there are no records of this phase of the castle's history and modern historians doubt this account.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=5}}{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|pp=106, 110}} The first castle was probably abandoned after 1093 when the Norman lordship of Glamorgan was created, changing the line of the frontier.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=106}}

In 1267, [[Gilbert de Clare, 7th Earl of Gloucester|Gilbert de Clare]], who held the [[Glamorgan#Lordship of Glamorgan|Lordship of Glamorgan]], seized the lands around the town of [[Senghenydd]] in the north of Glamorgan from their native Welsh ruler.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=106}}{{sfn|Newman|1995|p=315}}{{sfn|Davies|2006|p=282}} [[Caerphilly Castle]] was built to control the new territory and Castell Coch—strategically located between Cardiff and Caerphilly—was reoccupied.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=106}}{{sfn|Davies|2006|p=282}} A new castle was built in stone around the motte, comprising a shell-wall, a projecting circular tower, a [[gatehouse]] and a square hall above an [[undercroft]].{{sfn|Newman|1995|p=315}}{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|pp=106–107}} The north-west section of the walls was protected by a [[Talus (fortification)|talus]] and the sides of the motte were [[Counterscarp|scarped]] to increase their angle, all producing a small but powerful fortification.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=106}} Further work followed between 1268 and 1277, which added two large towers, a turning-bridge for the gatehouse and further protection to the north-west walls.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|pp=107–108}}{{efn|The historian David McLees, writing prior to the publication of the Royal Commission's survey on Castell Coch, suggested that the evidence for the chronology of the medieval castle was "inconclusive", but argued that the shell walls and stone apron might have been built in the mid-12th century, with the first round tower possibly built by the de Clares in the early to mid-13th century. The Royal Commission's survey noted that the comprehensive inventories of the de Clare possessions in 1263, and the lists of payments to their castle garrisons in the same year, make no reference to any castle at the site, and found no evidence for an earlier dating.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=106}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=8}}}}

On Gilbert's death, the castle passed to his widow [[Joan of Acre|Joan]] and around this time it was referred to as ''Castrum Rubeum'', Latin for "the Red Castle", probably after the colour of the [[Red sandstone|sandstone]] defences.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=105}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=7}} Gilbert's son, also named [[Gilbert de Clare, 8th Earl of Gloucester|Gilbert]], inherited the property in 1307.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=108}} He died at the [[Battle of Bannockburn]] in 1314, triggering an uprising of the [[native Welsh]] in the region.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=108}} Castell Coch was probably destroyed by the rebels in July 1314, and possibly [[slighted]] to put it beyond any further use; it was not rebuilt and the site was abandoned.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=108}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|pp=10–11}}

===15th–19th centuries===

====Bute ownership====
[[File:Burges's intent for Castell Coch, 1874.png|thumb|upright=1.1|[[William Burges]]'s plans for the reconstruction, showing the surviving medieval features (bottom) and his intentions for the new building (top)]]
Castell Coch remained derelict; the [[antiquarian]] [[John Leland (antiquary)|John Leland]], visiting around 1536, described it as "all in ruin, no big thing but high".{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=108}} The artist and illustrator [[Julius Caesar Ibbetson]] painted the castle in 1792, depicting substantial remains and a prominent tower, with a [[lime kiln]] in operation alongside the fortification.{{sfn|Rousham|1985|p=2}}{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=110}} Stone from the castle may have been robbed and used to feed the kilns during this period.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=11}} A similar view was sketched by an unknown artist in the early 19th century, showing more trees around the ruins; a few years later, Robert Drane recommended the site as a place for picnics and noted its abundance in wild [[garlic]].{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=110}}{{sfn|Brown|2011|pp=71–72}}{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=4}}

The ruins were acquired by the [[Marquess of Bute|Earls of Bute]] in 1760, when [[John Stuart, 1st Marquess of Bute|John Stuart]], the 3rd Earl and, from 1794, the 1st Marquess, married [[Viscount Windsor|Lady Charlotte Windsor]], adding her estates in South Wales to his inheritance.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=13}} John's grandson, [[John Crichton-Stuart, 2nd Marquess of Bute|John Crichton-Stuart]], developed the [[Cardiff Docks]] in the first half of the 19th century; although the docks were not especially profitable, they opened opportunities for the expansion of the coal industry in the South Wales valleys, making the Bute family extremely wealthy.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=13}}{{sfn|Davies|1981|p=272}} The 2nd Marquess carried out exploration for [[iron ore]] at Castell Coch in 1827 and considered establishing an ironworks there.{{sfn|Davies|1981|p=221}}

The 3rd Marquess of Bute, another [[John Crichton-Stuart, 3rd Marquess of Bute|John Crichton-Stuart]], inherited the castle and the family estates as a child in 1848.{{sfn|Hannah|2012|p=4}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=14}} On his coming of age, Bute's landed estates and industrial inheritance made him one of the wealthiest men in the world.{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=231}} He had a wide range of interests including archaeology, theology, linguistics and history.{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=231}} Interest in medieval architecture increased in Britain during the 19th century, and in 1850 the antiquarian [[G. T. Clark|George Clark]] surveyed Castell Coch and published his findings, the first major scholarly work about the castle.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=110}} The ruins were covered in rubble, ivy, brushwood and weeds; the keep had been largely destroyed and the gatehouse was so covered with debris that Clark failed to discover it.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=110}}{{sfn|Clark|1884|pp=360–364}} Nonetheless, Clark considered the external walls "tolerably perfect" and advised that the castle be conserved, complete with the ivy-covered stonework.{{sfn|Clark|1884|pp=362, 364}}

In 1871, Bute asked his chief Cardiff engineer, John McConnochie, to excavate and clear the castle ruins.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=112}}{{efn|John McConnochie is also called James McConnochie in some sources.}} The report on the investigations was produced by [[William Burges]], an architect with an interest in medieval architecture{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=112}} who had met Bute in 1865. The Marquess subsequently employed him to redevelop [[Cardiff Castle]] in the late 1860s, and the two men became close collaborators.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=3}}{{sfn|Redknap|2002|p=13}} Burges's lavishly illustrated report, which drew extensively on Clark's earlier work, laid out two options: either conserve the ruins or rebuild the castle to create a house for occasional occupation in the summer.{{sfn|Redknap|2002|pp=12–13}}{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=113}}{{sfn|Brown|2011|p=74}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=22}} On receipt of the report, Bute commissioned Burges to rebuild Castle Coch in a Gothic Revival style.{{sfn|Redknap|2002|pp=12–13}}{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=113}}

====Reconstruction====
[[File:Reconstruction of Castell Coch, 1875.jpg|thumb|left|Reconstruction of the castle in 1875, with a temporary bridge across the ditch (left) and the ruined Well Tower (right)]]
The reconstruction of Castell Coch was delayed until 1875, because of the demands of work at Cardiff Castle and an unfounded concern by the Marquess's trustees that he was facing bankruptcy.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=24}} On commencement, the Kitchen Tower, Hall Block and shell wall were rebuilt first, followed by the Well Tower and the Gatehouse, and the Keep Tower last.{{sfn|Brown|2011|p=75}}{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=113}} Burges's drawings for the proposed rebuilding survive at the Bute seat of [[Mount Stuart House|Mount Stuart]].{{sfn|Brown|2011|p=74}} The drawings were supplemented by a large number of wooden and plaster models, from smaller pieces to full-size models of furniture.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=271}}{{efn|name=Models}}

The bulk of the external work was complete by the end of 1879. The result closely followed Burges's original plans, with the exception of an additional watch tower intended to resemble a [[minaret]], and some defensive timber [[hoarding]]s, both of which were not undertaken.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=113}}{{sfn|Brown|2011|p=75}}{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=7}} Clark continued to advise Burges on historical aspects of the reconstruction and the architect tested the details of proposed features, such as the drawbridge and [[portcullis]], against surviving designs at other British castles.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=38}}{{sfn|Floud|1954|pp=7, 9}}

{{quote box|width=20em|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=right|quote="This concludes the survey of the ruins and my conjectural restoration. As for the latter I must claim your indulgence; for the knowledge of the military architecture of the Middle Ages is a long way from being as advanced as the knowledge of either domestic or ecclesiastical architecture. It is true that Viollet le Duc and Mr. G.T. Clark have taught us a great deal, but we are still very far behind hand and the restoration I have attempted will I hope be judged according to the measure of what is known or ought to be known".|source=—Extract from the report of William Burges on Castell Coch.{{sfn|Jones|2005|p=52}}}}

Burges's team of craftsmen at Castell Coch included many who had worked with him at Cardiff Castle and elsewhere.{{sfn|McLees|2005|pp=54–55}} [[John Starling Chapple|John Chapple]], his office manager, designed most of the furnishings and furniture,{{sfn|McLees|2005|pp=54–55}} and [[William Frame]] acted as [[clerk of works]].{{sfn|McLees|2005|pp=54–55}} [[Horatio Walter Lonsdale|Horatio Lonsdale]] was Burges's chief artist, painting extensive murals at the castle.{{sfn|McLees|2005|pp=54–55}} His main sculptor was [[Thomas Nicholls (sculptor)|Thomas Nicholls]], together with another long-time collaborator, the Italian sculptor [[Ceccardo Egidio Fucigna|Ceccardo Fucigna]].{{sfn|McLees|2005|pp=54–55}}

Stimulated by antiquarian writings about British viticulture, Bute decided to reintroduce commercial [[grape vine]]s into Britain in 1873.{{sfn|Pettigrew|1926|pp=26, 28}} He sent his gardener Andrew Pettigrew to France for training and planted a {{convert|3|acre|order=flip|adj=on}} vineyard just beneath the castle in 1875.{{sfn|Pettigrew|1926|pp=26, 28}}{{sfn|Lilwall-Smith|2005|p=239}} The first harvests were poor and the initial harvest in 1877 produced only 240 bottles.<ref name="Phil Carradice">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/wales/entries/bd5c99f2-cbd6-3069-911e-81a3ef61ff05|title=The Castell Coch Vineyard|publisher=BBC Wales|author=Phil Carradice|date=5 September 2014|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref>{{sfn|Pettigrew|1926|p=31}} ''[[Punch (magazine)|Punch]]'' magazine claimed that any wine produced would be so unpleasant that "it would take four men to drink it—two to hold the victim and one to pour the wine down his throat".{{sfn|Lilwall-Smith|2005|p=239}}{{sfn|Pettigrew|1926|p=31}}<ref name="WalesOnline">{{cite news|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/light-shed-vineyard-steeped-history-2406988|title=Light Shed on Vineyard Steeped in History|publisher=WalesOnline|date=22 February 2005}}</ref> By 1887, the output was 3,000 bottles of [[Sweetness of wine|sweet]] [[white wine]] of reasonable quality.<ref name="WalesOnline"/>{{sfn|Davies|1981|p=141}}{{sfn|Bunyard|Thomas|1906|p=251}} Bute persevered, commercial success followed and 40 [[hogshead]]s of wine, including a [[red wine|red varietal]] using [[Gamay]] grapes, were produced annually by 1894 to positive reviews.<ref name="WalesOnline"/>{{sfn|Davies|1981|p=141}}{{sfn|Bunyard|Thomas|1906|p=251}}{{sfn|Saintsbury|2008|p=293}}

Burges died in 1881 after catching a severe [[chills|chill]] during a site visit to the castle.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=272}}{{efn|For much of the 19th century, "a chill" was used as a diagnosis for illness involving a [[fever]] and associated [[chills]], in contrast to modern medical approaches which would regard a fever and chills as symptoms of an underlying disease.{{sfn|Misselbrook|2001|p=10}}}} His brother-in-law, the architect [[Richard Popplewell Pullan|Richard Pullan]], took over the commission and delegated most of the work to Frame, who directed the work on the interior until its completion in 1891.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=31}}{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=272}} Bute and his wife Gwendolen were consulted over the details of the interior decoration; replica family portraits based on those at Cardiff were commissioned to hang on the walls.{{sfn|Kightly|2005|p=77}}{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=13}} Clark approved of the result, commenting in 1884 that the restoration was in "excellent taste".{{sfn|Clark|1884|p=364}} An [[Oratory (worship)|oratory]] originally built on the roof of the Well Tower was removed before 1891 but in other respects the completed castle was left unaltered.{{sfn|Brown|2011|p=7}}

The castle was not greatly used; the Marquess rarely visited after its completion.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=31}} The property had probably only been intended for limited, informal use, for example as a retreat following picnics. Although it had reception rooms suitable for large gatherings, it had only three bedrooms and was too far from Cardiff for casual visits.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=18}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=24}}{{efn|name=Dunster|For comparison, on the other side of the [[Severn Estuary]], [[Dunster Castle]], a motte and shell-keep medieval castle, was being remodelled by the architect [[Anthony Salvin]] at around this time, specifically to enable the property to meet late 19th-century standards of facilities and accommodation.{{sfn|Garnett|2003|pp=32, 35}}}} The restored castle initially received little interest from the architectural community, possibly because the total rebuilding of the castle ran counter to the increasingly popular late-Victorian philosophy of conserving older buildings and monuments.{{sfn|Brown|2011|pp=68–71, 75–76}}

===20th–21st centuries===
[[File:Castell Coch courtyard.jpg|thumb|upright|The courtyard]]
Bute died in 1900 and his widow, the Marchioness, was given a [[Life estate|life interest]] in Castell Coch; during her mourning, she and her daughter, Lady Margaret Crichton-Stuart, occupied the castle and made occasional visits thereafter.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=31}}{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=276}} Production in the castle vineyards ceased during the [[First World War]] due to the shortages of the sugar needed for the [[Chaptalization|fermentation process]], and in 1920 the vineyards were uprooted.<ref name="WalesOnline"/> [[John Crichton-Stuart, 4th Marquess of Bute|John]], the 4th Marquess, acquired the castle in 1932 but made little use of it.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=18}} He also began to reduce the family's investments in South Wales.<ref name="Benham 2001 2">{{cite web | url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/nra/onlinelists/GB%200214%20DA_cld.pdf | title=Glamorgan Estate of Lord Bute collection | accessdate=16 March 2015 | last=Benham| first=Stephen |date=March 2001 | publisher=National Archives| page = 2}}</ref> The coal trade had declined after 1918 and industry had suffered during the [[Economic history of the United Kingdom#Postwar stagnation|depression of the 1920s]];{{sfn|Jenkins|2002|pp=26, 33}}{{sfn|Nicholas|1872|p=461}} by 1938, the great majority of the family interests, including the coal mines and docks, had been sold off or nationalised.<ref name="Benham 2001 2"/>

The [[John Crichton-Stuart, 5th Marquess of Bute|5th Marquess of Bute]], another John, succeeded in 1947 and, in 1950, he placed the castle in the care of the [[Ministry of Works (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Works]]. The Marquess also disposed of Cardiff Castle, which he gave to the city, removing the family portraits from the castle before doing so. In turn, the paintings in Castell Coch were removed by the ministry and sent to Cardiff,{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=13}} the [[National Museum of Wales]] providing alternatives from their collection for Castell Coch.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=13}} Academic interest in the property grew, with publications in the 1950s and 1960s exploring its artistic and architectural value.{{sfn|Brown|2011|pp=75–76}} Since 1984, the property has been administered by [[Cadw]], an agency of the [[Welsh Government]], and is open to the public; it received 69,466 visitors in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tourismhelp.co.uk/objview.asp?object_id=670|title=Visits to Tourist Attractions in Wales 2011: Report for Visit Wales |publisher=Cadw|author=Claire Peate|p=40|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref> The castle has also been used as a location for filming.{{sfn|Creighton|Higham|2003|p=65}}

The castle's exposed position causes it to suffer from [[Damp (structural)#Rain penetration|penetrating damp]] and periodic restoration work has been necessary.{{sfn|Kightly|2005|p=77}}<ref name=CaseStudy>{{cite web|url=http://cadw.wales.gov.uk/docs/cadw/publications/Position%20Statement%202007_EN.pdf|title=Case Study: Conservation Achievements, Castell Coch |publisher=Cadw|author=Historic Wales and Welsh Assembly Government|p=38|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> The stone tiles on the roof were replaced by slate in 1972, a major programme was carried out on the Keep in 2007 and interior conservation work was undertaken in 2011 to address problems in Lady Bute's Bedroom, where damp had begun to damage the finishings.{{sfn|Kightly|2005|p=77}}<ref name=CaseStudy/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cadw.wales.gov.uk/historicenvironment/conservation/conservationcadwsites/castellcochcasestudy/?lang=en|title=Castell Coch – Lady Bute’s Bedroom|publisher=Cadw|accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=report>{{cite web|url=http://historicwales.gov.uk/files/pdf-listed-building.php?ids=22942&lang=ENG|title=Historic Wales Report|publisher=Historic Wales|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref>

The original furnishings, many of which the Marquess removed in 1950, have mostly been recovered and returned to their original locations in the castle.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=31}} Two stained-glass panels from the demolished chapel, lost since 1901, were rediscovered at an auction in 2010 and were bought by Cadw for £125,000 in 2011.<ref name="bbc.co.uk">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/legacy/waleshistory/2011/04/castell_coch_william_burges_stained_glass_panels.html|title=Burges' Stained Glass Panels Return Home to Castell Coch|author=Phil Carradice|publisher=BBC Wales|date=1 April 2011|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>

==Architecture==

===Overview===
Castell Coch occupies a stretch of woodland on the slopes above the village of [[Tongwynlais]] and the River Taff, about {{convert|6.6|mi|order=flip}} north-west of the centre of Cardiff.<ref>[https://www.google.co.uk/maps/dir/Cardiff+Castle,+Castle+Street,+Cardiff/Castell+Coch,+Tongwynlais,+Cardiff+CF15+7JS,+United+Kingdom/@51.508925,-3.2933608,12z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m13!4m12!1m5!1m1!1s0x486e1cafe371b7d9:0x4405a12f19bc6673!2m2!1d-3.182207!2d51.481764!1m5!1m1!1s0x486e1a3453043a0b:0xe8e0bda21f08e0ed!2m2!1d-3.254633!2d51.535807 Google Maps], Google Inc., Retrieved 7 April 2015</ref>{{Sfn|Cormack|1982|p=172}} The architecture is High Victorian Gothic Revival in style, influenced by contemporary 19th-century French restorations.<ref name="Castell Coch, Tongwynlais">{{cite web|title=Castell Coch, Tongwynlais|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/wa-13644-castell-coch-tongwynlais|publisher=British Listed Buildings|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref> Its design combines the surviving elements of the medieval castle with 19th-century additions to produce a building which the historian Charles Kightly considered "the crowning glory of the Gothic Revival" in Britain. It is protected under UK law as a Grade&nbsp;I listed building due to its exceptional architectural and historical interest.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=3}}<ref name=report/><ref name="Castell Coch, Tongwynlais"/>{{sfn|Kightly|2005|p=74}}

===Exterior===
[[File:Diagram of Castell Coch.png|thumb|upright=1.4|right|Diagram of the castle in the 21st century; A&nbsp;– Kitchen Tower; B&nbsp;– Courtyard; C&nbsp;– Hall Block; D&nbsp;– Well Tower; E&nbsp;– Gatehouse; F&nbsp;– Keep]]
The castle comprises three circular towers—the Keep, the Kitchen Tower and the Well Tower—along with the Hall Block, the Gatehouse and a shell wall; the buildings almost entirely encase the original motte in stone.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|pp=113–114}} The older parts of the castle are constructed from crudely laid red [[sandstone]] rubble and grey [[limestone]], the 19th-century additions in more precisely cut red [[Pennant sandstone]].{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=113}}{{sfn|Ashurst|Dimes|2011|pp=70–71}} A ditch is cut out of the rock in front of the Gatehouse and leads to an eastern approach road.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|pp=106, 113}} The castle is surrounded by woodland and the 19th-century vineyards below it have been converted into a golf course.<ref name="Phil Carradice"/> In 1850, George Clark recorded an "outer court" of which nothing remains; this may, in fact, have been the traces of the earlier lime kiln operations around the site.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=111}}

The Gatehouse is reached across a wooden bridge, incorporating a drawbridge.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=8}} Burges intended the bridge to copy those of medieval castles, which he believed were designed to be easily set on fire in the event of attack.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=8}} The Gatehouse was fitted with a wooden defensive [[Hoarding (castle)|bretache]]{{efn|A bretache is a defensive structure overhanging a castle wall. Commonly of timber, it allowed defenders to drop damaging objects onto attackers below. A similar bretache, since removed, was constructed by Burges on the walls at [[Cardiff Castle]].}} and, above the entrance, Burges sited a portcullis and a glazed statue of the [[Madonna and Child]] sculpted by Ceccardo Fucigna.{{sfn|McLees|2005|pp=54–55}}{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=8}}

The Keep is {{convert|12|m}} in diameter with a square, spurred base; in the 13th century there would have been an adjacent turret, on the south-west side, containing latrines, but few traces remain.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=121}} There is no evidence that the tower that Burges termed a [[keep]] would have fulfilled this function in the medieval period and he appears to have chosen the name because of his initial decision to locate the bedrooms of Lord and Lady Bute in the rebuilt tower.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=121}} The Kitchen Tower is also {{convert|12|m}} across and rests on a square, spurred base.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=116}} It was originally two storeys high and contained the medieval kitchen; Burgess raised its height and gave it a conical roof and chimneys.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=116}} The walls of these two towers are around {{convert|10|ft|order=flip}} thick at the base, thinning to {{convert|2|ft|order=flip}} at the top.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=8}} The Well Tower at {{convert|11.5|m}} in diameter is slightly narrower than the Keep or Kitchen Tower, with a well in its lowest chamber sunk into the ground.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|pp=121–123}} The Well Tower lacks the spurs of the other two towers and has a flat rather than curved back, facing onto the courtyard, similar to some of the towers built at Caerphilly by the de Clares.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=122}}

[[File:Keep Tower, Castell Coch.jpg|thumb|left|The conical roofs of the Well Tower (left) and Keep (right), topped by elaborate weather vanes and chimneys]]

The towers contribute to what the architectural writer [[Charles Handley-Read]] considered the castle's "sculptural and dramatic exterior".{{sfn|Ferriday|1963|p=208}} Almost equal in diameter, but of differing conical roof designs and heights, and topped with copper-gilt weather vanes, they combine to produce a romantic appearance,{{sfn|Newman|1995|p=315}}{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|pp=106, 113}}{{sfn|Lilwall-Smith|2005|p=240}} which Matthew Williams described as bringing "a Wagnerian {{not a typo|flavor}} to the Taff Valley".{{sfn|Williams|2004|p=11}}

{{quote box|width=20em|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=right|quote="As nearly every Castle in the country has been ruined for more than two centuries&nbsp;...it is not surprising that no examples are to be found. But we may form a very fair idea of the case if we consult contemporary [manuscripts] and if we do we find nearly an equal number of towers with flat roofs as those with pointed roofs. The case appears to me to be thus: if a tower presented a good situation for military engines, it had a flat top; if the contrary, it had a high roof to guarantee the defenders from the rain and the lighter sorts of missiles".|source=—Burges defending his decision to feature conical roofs in the light of doubtful historical evidence.{{sfn|Girouard|1979|p=340}}}}

The design of the towers was influenced by the work of the contemporary French architect [[Eugène Viollet-le-Duc]], including his restorations of [[Cité de Carcassonne|Carcassone]] and the châteaus of [[Aigle]] and [[Château de Chillon|Chillon]].{{sfn|Redknap|2002|p=13}} While the exterior of Castell Coch is relatively true to English 13th-century medieval design—albeit heavily influenced by the Gothic Revival movement—the inclusion of the conical roofs, which more closely resemble those of fortifications in France or Switzerland than Britain, is historically inaccurate.{{sfn|Redknap|2002|p=13}}{{sfn|Kightly|2005|p=74}}{{sfn|Girouard|1979|p=340}}{{sfn|Creighton|Higham|2003|p=63}} Although he mounted a historical defence (see box), Burges chose the roofs mainly for architectural effect, arguing that they appeared "more picturesque", and to provide additional room for accommodation in the castle.{{sfn|Girouard|1979|p=340}}

The three towers lead into a small oval courtyard that sits on the top of the motte, about {{convert|19.5|m}} across lengthways.{{sfn|Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Wales|2000|p=116}} Cantilevered galleries and wall-walks run around the inside of the courtyard with neat and orderly woodwork; the historian [[Peter Floud]] critiqued it as "perhaps too much like the backcloth for an historical pageant".{{sfn|Lilwall-Smith|2005|p=240}}{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=9}} Burges reconstructed the shell wall that runs along the north-west side of the courtyard {{convert|3|ft|3|in|order=flip}} thick, complete with arrow holes and a battlement.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=18}}

===Interior===
The Keep, the Well Tower and the Kitchen Tower incorporate a series of apartments, of which the main sequence, the Castellan's Rooms, lies within the Keep. The Hall, the Drawing Room, Lord Bute's Bedroom and Lady Bute's Bedroom form a suite of rooms that exemplify the High Victorian Gothic style of 19th century Britain. Unlike the exterior of the castle, which deliberately imitated the architecture of the 13th century, the interior was purely High Victorian in style.{{sfn|Brown|2011|p=75}} On Burges's decoration of Cardiff Castle and Castell Coch, Handley-Read wrote: "I have yet to see any High Victorian interiors from the hand, very largely, of one designer, to equal either in homogeneity or completeness, in quality of execution or originality of conception the best of the interiors of the Welsh castles. For sheer power of intoxication, Burges stand[s] unrivalled."{{sfn|Ferriday|1963|p=209}}

====The Banqueting Hall====
[[File:Castell Coch - Banqueting Room.JPG|thumb|The Banqueting Hall]]
The Banqueting Hall is {{convert|20|by|30|ft|order=flip}} across with an {{convert|35|ft|order=flip|adj=on}} ceiling, and occupies the whole of the first floor of the Hall Block.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=12}} Burges persuaded Bute and the antiquarian George Clark that the medieval hall would have stood on the first floor.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=38}} His original plan saw access via one of two equally circuitous routes through the Well Tower or around the entire internal gallery to enter the hall through a passage next to the Drawing Room.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=38}} Neither approach was acceptable to Bute and at a late stage, around 1878/9, the present entrance was created by expanding a window at the head of the internal gallery.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=38}}

The hall is austere; the architect John Newman critiqued its decoration as "dilute" and "unfocused", Crook as "anaemic".{{sfn|Newman|1995|p=317}}{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=266}} It features [[stencil]]led ceilings and murals which resemble medieval manuscripts. The murals were designed by Horatio Lonsdale and executed by Campbell, Smith & Company.{{sfn|Girouard|1979|p=341}}{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=266}} The furniture is by John Chapple, made in Lord Bute's workshops at Cardiff.{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=266}} The tapered chimney of the room, modelled on 15th-century French equivalents, contains a statue carved by Thomas Nicholls.{{sfn|Girouard|1979|p=341}} Although the architectural historian [[Mark Girouard]] suggested that the statue depicts the Hebrew [[King David]], most historians believe that it shows [[Lucius of Britain]], according to legend the founder of the [[diocese of Llandaff]] in nearby Cardiff.{{sfn|Lilwall-Smith|2005|p=240}}{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=12}}{{sfn|Girouard|1979|p=341}}

====The Drawing Room====
[[File:Drawing room walls, Castell Coch.jpg|thumb|left|The Drawing Room]]
The octagonal Drawing Room occupies the first and second floors of the Keep.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=13}} The ceiling is supported by vaulted stone ribs modelled on Viollet-Le-Duc's work at [[Château de Coucy]] and the lower and upper halves of the room are divided by a [[minstrels' gallery]].{{sfn|Crook|2013|pp=267–268}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=29}} The original plans for the space involved two chambers, one on each floor, and the new design was adopted only in 1879, Burges noting at the time that he intended to "indulge in a little more ornament" than elsewhere in the castle.{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=267}}{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=14}}

The decoration of the room focuses on what Newman described as the "intertwined themes [of] the fecundity of nature and the fragility of life".{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=13}}{{sfn|Newman|1995|p=318}} A fireplace by Thomas Nicholls features the [[Moirai|Three Fates]], the trio of Greek goddesses who are depicted spinning, measuring and cutting the thread of life.{{sfn|Lilwall-Smith|2005|p=240}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=43}} The ceiling's vaulting is carved with butterflies, reaching up to a golden sunburst at the apex of the room, while plumed birds fly up into a starry sky in the intervening sections.{{sfn|Crook|2013|pp=267–268}}{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=15}} Around the room, 58 panels, each depicting a unique plant, are surmounted by a mural showing animals from [[Aesop's Fables]]. Carved birds, lizards and other wildlife decorate the doorways.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=15}}

The historian Terry Measham wrote that the Drawing Room and Lady Bute's Bedroom, "so powerful in their effect, are the two most important interiors in the castle."{{sfn|Measham|1978|p=2}} The architectural writer Andrew Lilwall-Smith considered the Drawing Room to be "Burges's pièce de résistance", encapsulating his "romantic vision of the Middle Ages".{{sfn|Lilwall-Smith|2005|p=240}} The decoration of the ceiling, which was carried out while Burges was alive, differs in tone from the treatment of the murals, and the decoration of Lady Bute's Bedroom, which were both completed, under the direction of William Frame and Horatio Lonsdale respectively, after Burges's death.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=43}}{{sfn|Williams|2003|pp=271–272}} Burges's work is distinctively High Gothic in style, while the later efforts are more influenced by the softer colours and character of the [[Aestheticism|Aesthetic movement]], which had grown in popularity by the 1880s.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=272}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=43}}

====Lord Bute's Bedroom====
In comparison to other rooms within the castle, Lord Bute's Bedroom, sited above the Winch Room, is relatively small and simple.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=46}} The original plan had Bute's personal accommodation in the Keep but the expansion of the Drawing Room to a double-height room in 1879 required a late change of plan.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=29}} The bedroom contains an ornately carved fireplace.{{Sfn|Quinn|2008|p=144}} Doors lead off the room to an internal balcony overlooking the courtyard and to the bretache over the gate arch.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=46}} The furniture is mainly by Chapple and post-dates Burges, although the washstand and dressing table are pared-down versions of two pieces – the [[Narcissus washstand|Narcissus Washstand]] and the Crocker Dressing Table – that Burges made for his own home in London, [[The Tower House]].{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=47}}

This bedroom is also less richly ornamented than many in the castle, making extensive use of plain, stencilled geometrical patterns on the walls.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=16}} Crook suggested this provided some "spartan" relief before the culmination of the castle in Lady Bute's Bedroom but Floud considered the result "thin" and drab in comparison with the more richly decorated chambers.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=16}}{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=269}} The bedroom would have been impractical for regular use, lacking wardrobes and other storage.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=275}}

====Lady Bute's Bedroom====
[[File:Castell Coch - Lady Bute's bedroom.jpg|thumb|Lady Bute's Bedroom]]
Lady Bute's Bedroom comprises the upper two floors of the Keep, with a [[coffer]]ed, double-dome ceiling that rises up into the tower's conical roof.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=17}} The room was completed after Burges's death and, although he had created an outline model for the room's structure, which survives, he did not undertake detailed plans for its decoration.{{sfn|Williams|2003|pp=271–272}}{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=269}}{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=17}}{{efn|name=Models|The model of Lady Bute's Bedroom was photographed for an article by W. Howell in 1951 but then vanished, presumed destroyed. It was rediscovered at the Bute property of [[Dumfries House]], [[Ayrshire]], in 2002. The other models were stored at Cardiff Castle, in the Model Room of the Black Tower but were probably destroyed in the late 1940s.{{sfn|Williams|2003|pp=269, 271}}}} His team attempted to fulfil his vision for the room—"would Mr Burges have done it?" William Frame asked Nicholls in a letter of 1887—but the interior decoration was the work of Lonsdale between 1887 and 1888, with considerable involvement from Bute and his wife.{{sfn|Williams|2003|pp=271–272}}{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=269}}

The room is circular, with the window embrasures forming a sequence of [[Arcade (architecture)|arches]] around the outside.{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=269}} It is richly decorated, with [[love]] as the theme, displaying carved monkeys, nesting birds and pomegranates, images taken from 15th-century manuscripts.{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=269}}{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=17}} Lord Bute thought the monkeys inappropriately "lascivious".{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=269}} Above the fireplace is a winged statue of [[Cupid and Psyche|Psyche]], the Greek goddess of the soul, carrying a heart-shaped shield which displays the arms of the Bute family.{{sfn|Lilwall-Smith|2005|p=240}} The washbasin, designed by John Chapple, has [[cistern]]s for hot and cold water, covered with [[crenellation|crenellated]] towers.{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=269}} The Marchioness's scarlet and gold bed is the most notable piece of furniture in the room, modelled on a medieval original drawn by Viollet-le-Duc.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=49}}{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=269}} Crook described the bed as being "medieval to the point of acute discomfort".{{sfn|Crook|2013|p=269}}

The bedroom is Moorish in style, a popular inspiration in mid-Victorian interior design, and echoes earlier work by Burges in the Arab Room at Cardiff Castle and in the chancel at [[St Mary's, Studley Royal|St Mary's Church]] at Studley Royal in Yorkshire.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=17}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=49}} Lilwall-Smith likened the chamber, with its "Moorish-looking dome, maroon-and-gold painted furniture and large, low bed decorated with glass crystal orbs", to a scene from the ''[[One Thousand and One Nights|Arabian Nights]]''.{{sfn|Lilwall-Smith|2005|p=240}} Peter Floud criticised the eclectic nature of this Moorish theme and contrasted it unfavourably with the more consistent style Burges applied to the Arab Room, suggesting that it gave the bedroom an overly theatrical, even pantomime-like, character.{{sfn|Floud|1954|pp=16–17}} The historian Matthew Williams considered that Lonsdale's efforts lack the imagination and flair that Burges himself might have brought to the room.{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=272}}

====Other rooms====
The Windlass Room, or Winch Room, is in the Gatehouse, entered from the Drawing Room.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=15}} It contains a working mechanism for operating the drawbridge and the portcullis.{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=45}} The equipment was originally intended for the second floor, which Burges considered the most historically authentic location.{{sfn|Floud|1954|pp=15–16}} When later design modifications led him to move Lord Bute's Bedroom into that space, the equipment was simplified and placed on the first floor.{{sfn|Floud|1954|pp=15–16}} The Windlass Room includes [[murder holes]], which Burges thought would have enabled medieval inhabitants of the castle to pour [[Early thermal weapons|boiling water and oil]] on attackers.{{sfn|Floud|1954|p=16}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=45}}

An oratory, originally fitted to the roof of the Well Tower but removed before 1891, was decorated with twenty stained glass windows.{{sfn|Brown|2011|p=7}}{{sfn|McLees|2005|p=52}} Ten of these windows are displayed at Cardiff Castle, while the other ten are displayed on site; two missing windows having been returned to the castle in 2011.<ref name="bbc.co.uk"/> Other rooms in the castle include Lady Margaret Bute's Bedroom, the servants' hall and the kitchen.{{sfn|McLees|2005|pp=50–53}}

