==Landscape – Site of Special Scientific Interest==
[[File:Castle Coch from A470.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|View of the castle and the surrounding beech woodland in December 2012]]
The woods surrounding the castle, known as the Taff Gorge complex, are among the most westerly natural [[beech]] woodlands in the British Isles.<ref name=SiteofSpecialScienticInterest>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccgc.gov.uk/landscape--wildlife/protecting-our-landscape/special-landscapes--sites/protected-landscapes-and-sites/sssis/sssi-sites/idoc.ashx?docid=0bbe537d-685f-4287-878c-8d9f9ac718ab&version=-1|title=Site of Special Scientific Interest|publisher=Countryside Council for Wales|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref> They contain [[dog's mercury]], [[Allium ursinum|ransoms]], [[sanicle]]s, [[bird's-nest orchid]], [[greater butterfly-orchid]] and [[Monotropa hypopitys|yellow bird's nest]] plants.<ref name=SiteofSpecialScienticInterest/> The area has unusual rock outcrops, which show the point where [[Devonian]] [[Old Red Sandstone]] and [[Carboniferous Limestone]] beds meet; the Castell Coch Quarry is in the vicinity.{{Sfn|Strahan|Cantrill|1902|pp=27–28}} To the southeast of the castle, a nine-hole [[golf course]] occupies the site of the former vineyard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.welshgolfcourses.com/south/castellcoch.php|title=Castell Coch Golf Club|publisher=Welshgolfcourses.com|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref> The area is protected as the [[Castell Coch Woodlands and Road Section]] Site of Special Scientific Interest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccgc.gov.uk/landscape--wildlife/protecting-our-landscape/special-landscapes--sites/protected-landscapes-and-sites/sssis/sssi-sites/castell-coch-woodlands.aspx|title=Castell Coch Woodlands and Road Section|publisher=Countryside Council for Wales|accessdate=15 March 2015}}</ref>

